Explanation:
- The deleteEmployee method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID}", method = RequestMethod.DELETE) in ManagerController. That exact value is the full endpoint path (there is no class-level @RequestMapping prefix), and the mapping explicitly specifies RequestMethod.DELETE.
- Because the method attribute is set to RequestMethod.DELETE, only the DELETE method is allowed for this mapping in the source code. There is no mapping in this file that declares HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH, GET, PUT or POST for the same path with the {employeeID} segment.
- Other operations (GET, POST, PUT) exist for the path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees (without {employeeID}), but those are different endpoints and do not affect the /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID} mapping.
- I did not assume any framework default behaviors (such as automatic HEAD support for GET) â€” the result is determined strictly from the annotations present in the provided source.
